08/02/2005
ANKARA, Turkey -- The main council of Turkey's Human Rights Advisory Board (HRAB) resigned Monday (7 February), citing political pressure. 
According to board president Ibrahim Kaboglu, the four members decided to resign because they cannot function freely. 
The 70-member HRAB was established in early 2003, in line with EU criteria.
In other news Monday, Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan began a trip to the region devastated by the December tsunami. 
His stops include Indonesia, Malaysia, Thailand, the Maldives and Sri Lanka. 
(Asia Pulse - 08/02/05; NTV - 07/02/05)
